 <i>tūn</i>) of the peasants’. Old English <i>ceorl</i> denoted originally a free peasant of the lowest rank, later (but probably already before the Norman conquest) a tenant in pure villeinage, a serf or bondsman.","Irish: altered form of   Carlin  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"William de Cherleton, I was born in 1180, in Wrockwardine, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom. He had at least 1 son with Cherleton."},"et":{"1180–":"1180–Surnud","1185–Female":"1185–Surnud","1204–1233":"1204–1233","1180–Male":"1180–Surnud","1204":"1204","1233":"1233","1185":"1185","1180":"1180","Wrockwardine, Shropshire, England":"Wrockwardine, Shropshire, England"},"fi":{"1180–":"1180–Kuollut","1185–Female":"1185–Kuollut","1204–1233":"1204–1233","1180–Male":"1180–Kuollut","1204":"1204","1233":"1233","1185":"1185","1180":"1180","Wrockwardine, Shropshire, England":"Wrockwardine, Shropshire, England"},"fr":{"1180–":"1180–Décédé","1185–Female":"1185–Décédée","1204–1233":"1204–1233","1180–Male":"1180–Décédé","1204":"1204","1233":"1233","1185":"1185","1180":"1180","Wrockwardine, Shropshire, England":"Wrockwardine, Shropshire, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"William de Cherleton, I est né en 1180, à Wrockwardine, Shropshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni. I